partial mu A mu equal to O. OK?

00:01:10.425 --> 00:01:12.960 align:middle line:90%


00:01:12.960 --> 00:01:15.690 align:middle line:84%
And in particular, the
action is particularly

00:01:15.690 --> 00:01:22.330 align:middle line:84%
simple for xi equal to 1,
in which case we just have--

00:01:22.330 --> 00:01:23.950 align:middle line:84%
actually we just
have [INAUDIBLE]..

00:01:23.950 --> 00:01:30.550 align:middle line:90%


00:01:30.550 --> 00:01:31.450 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:01:31.450 --> 00:01:35.600 align:middle line:84%
So as if you just have 4
decoupled massless scalar.

00:01:35.600 --> 00:01:36.100 align:middle line:90%
OK?

00:01:36.100 --> 00:01:39.520 align:middle line:84%
As if you just have
4 massless scalar.

00:01:39.520 --> 00:01:42.070 align:middle line:84%
And the equation of motion
is actually all very simple.

00:01:42.070 --> 00:01:46.390 align:middle line:90%


00:01:46.390 --> 00:01:47.860 align:middle line:90%
So we can just proceed.

00:01:47.860 --> 00:01:56.190 align:middle line:84%
Copy our result before
for massless scalar.

00:01:56.190 --> 00:01:59.040 align:middle line:84%
And just treat each A
mu as a massless scalar,

00:01:59.040 --> 00:02:01.420 align:middle line:90%
and then we can just do it.

00:02:01.420 --> 00:02:08.970 align:middle line:84%
For example, the canonical
momentum conjugate to A mu

00:02:08.970 --> 00:02:15.085 align:middle line:84%
would be just a mu
dot, just A mu dot.

00:02:15.085 --> 00:02:15.585 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:02:15.585 --> 00:02:19.230 align:middle line:90%


00:02:19.230 --> 00:02:23.805 align:middle line:84%
So the canonical quantization
condition, then, is given by--

00:02:23.805 --> 00:02:43.540 align:middle line:90%


00:02:43.540 --> 00:02:48.670 align:middle line:84%
and we can also just
straightforwardly write down

00:02:48.670 --> 00:02:56.020 align:middle line:84%
A mu, the expansion for-- the
operator expansion for A mu.

00:02:56.020 --> 00:03:07.485 align:middle line:90%


00:03:07.485 --> 00:03:07.985 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:03:07.985 --> 00:03:11.020 align:middle line:90%


00:03:11.020 --> 00:03:13.460 align:middle line:90%
So we have four of them.

00:03:13.460 --> 00:03:16.450 align:middle line:90%
So again, we will--

00:03:16.450 --> 00:03:19.810 align:middle line:84%
instead of writing them
as 4 massless scalar,

00:03:19.810 --> 00:03:24.250 align:middle line:84%
we will-- as we did before,
for the Coulomb gauge case,

00:03:24.250 --> 00:03:27.640 align:middle line:84%
we introduce a
polarization vector.

00:03:27.640 --> 00:03:29.810 align:middle line:84%
So we will introduce
a polarization vector.

00:03:29.810 --> 00:03:31.510 align:middle line:84%
So there are four
possible things.

00:03:31.510 --> 00:03:33.380 align:middle line:90%
There are four components.

00:03:33.380 --> 00:03:37.940 align:middle line:84%
So there are four
possible polarizations--

00:03:37.940 --> 00:03:38.440 align:middle line:90%
times.

00:03:38.440 --> 00:04:12.070 align:middle line:90%


00:04:12.070 --> 00:04:13.810 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:04:13.810 --> 00:04:16.089 align:middle line:90%
So we just get that.

00:04:16.089 --> 00:04:25.320 align:middle line:84%
So this epsilon mu alpha for
alpha equal to 0, 1, 2, 3--

00:04:25.320 --> 00:04:27.640 align:middle line:84%
so these are four
polarization vectors.

00:04:27.640 --> 00:04:28.140 align:middle line:90%
OK?

00:04:28.140 --> 00:04:36.690 align:middle line:90%


00:04:36.690 --> 00:04:37.680 align:middle line:90%
You can choose.

00:04:37.680 --> 00:04:44.250 align:middle line:84%
You can just choose, say, 1,
0, 0, 0, 0, 1, 0, 0, et cetera.

00:04:44.250 --> 00:04:47.670 align:middle line:84%
And then this just like
four decoupled scalar, OK?

00:04:47.670 --> 00:04:51.390 align:middle line:84%
But this way introduces
a polarization vector,

00:04:51.390 --> 00:04:56.240 align:middle line:84%
allowing to write them
in a more general way.

00:04:56.240 --> 00:04:57.445 align:middle line:90%
So we normally pick--

00:04:57.445 --> 00:05:05.070 align:middle line:90%


00:05:05.070 --> 00:05:09.870 align:middle line:84%
for example, the 0-th component,
the 0-th polarization vector

00:05:09.870 --> 00:05:14.080 align:middle line:84%
just to be along the
time direction, OK?

00:05:14.080 --> 00:05:17.090 align:middle line:84%
So just along the
time direction.

00:05:17.090 --> 00:05:21.980 align:middle line:84%
And then we also
introduce another--

00:05:21.980 --> 00:05:25.490 align:middle line:84%
so the number 3,
we introduce to be

00:05:25.490 --> 00:05:28.940 align:middle line:84%
proportional to the
direction of the momentum.

00:05:28.940 --> 00:05:33.910 align:middle line:90%


00:05:33.910 --> 00:05:35.470 align:middle line:90%
So this is proportional to the--

00:05:35.470 --> 00:05:39.100 align:middle line:84%
parallel to the momentum,
to the spatial momentum.

00:05:39.100 --> 00:05:43.990 align:middle line:90%
So the k mu here would be--

00:05:43.990 --> 00:05:46.490 align:middle line:90%
because this is massless.

00:05:46.490 --> 00:05:47.650 align:middle line:90%
So we just have this.

00:05:47.650 --> 00:05:49.510 align:middle line:84%
OK so so the 0-th
component is just

00:05:49.510 --> 00:05:53.210 align:middle line:90%
equal to the magnitude of k.

00:05:53.210 --> 00:06:02.870 align:middle line:84%
And then we take the epsilon 1,
2 epsilon mu, then 1, 2 to be,

00:06:02.870 --> 00:06:06.725 align:middle line:84%
let's say, orthogonal
to the momentum.

00:06:06.725 --> 00:06:09.790 align:middle line:90%


00:06:09.790 --> 00:06:18.940 align:middle line:84%
So these are called the
transverse polarizations.

00:06:18.940 --> 00:06:25.000 align:middle line:90%


00:06:25.000 --> 00:06:30.280 align:middle line:84%
So we take them also to be
orthogonal to 0-th component.

00:06:30.280 --> 00:06:32.620 align:middle line:90%
That means there's no--

00:06:32.620 --> 00:06:35.650 align:middle line:84%
the time component for
1, 2 will be 0, too,

00:06:35.650 --> 00:06:39.010 align:middle line:84%
and then also it should be
proportional-- it should also

00:06:39.010 --> 00:06:40.720 align:middle line:90%
be orthogonal to the momentum.

00:06:40.720 --> 00:06:45.730 align:middle line:90%


00:06:45.730 --> 00:06:51.260 align:middle line:84%
So we take, also, them to
be orthogonal to each other.

00:06:51.260 --> 00:06:58.278 align:middle line:90%


00:06:58.278 --> 00:06:59.022 align:middle line:90%
Eta mu nu.

00:06:59.022 --> 00:07:00.855 align:middle line:84%
We take them to be
orthogonal to each other.

00:07:00.855 --> 00:07:06.370 align:middle line:90%


00:07:06.370 --> 00:07:10.930 align:middle line:84%
This is the normal,
orthonormal condition.

00:07:10.930 --> 00:07:18.060 align:middle line:90%


00:07:18.060 --> 00:07:19.200 align:middle line:90%
OK?

00:07:19.200 --> 00:07:21.240 align:middle line:84%
Take these spaces
to be orthonormal.

00:07:21.240 --> 00:07:23.400 align:middle line:90%
And then this is also complete.

00:07:23.400 --> 00:07:27.900 align:middle line:84%
Means that if I sum over
different alpha and beta--

00:07:27.900 --> 00:07:34.130 align:middle line:90%


00:07:34.130 --> 00:07:36.650 align:middle line:84%
and actually I can
get back to eta mu nu.

00:07:36.650 --> 00:07:39.160 align:middle line:90%
OK?

00:07:39.160 --> 00:07:41.620 align:middle line:84%
So this is called
the completeness.

00:07:41.620 --> 00:07:44.440 align:middle line:90%
So they form a complete basis.

00:07:44.440 --> 00:07:48.234 align:middle line:84%
So any Lorentz vector can
be expanded in terms of it.

00:07:48.234 --> 00:07:53.340 align:middle line:90%


00:07:53.340 --> 00:08:00.950 align:middle line:84%
So if we take, say, k
to be the z-direction,

00:08:00.950 --> 00:08:03.980 align:middle line:84%
then the simplest choice
would be, say, you just do--

00:08:03.980 --> 00:08:08.120 align:middle line:90%


00:08:08.120 --> 00:08:09.395 align:middle line:90%
so we just have that.

00:08:09.395 --> 00:08:31.860 align:middle line:90%


00:08:31.860 --> 00:08:33.270 align:middle line:90%
OK, so this is simplest.

00:08:33.270 --> 00:08:36.510 align:middle line:84%
But you can consider more
general polarization.

00:08:36.510 --> 00:08:40.210 align:middle line:90%


00:08:40.210 --> 00:08:45.760 align:middle line:84%
And so now, if you
plug in this expansion,

00:08:45.760 --> 00:08:48.460 align:middle line:84%
as we do, for the scalar,
and then you plug in

00:08:48.460 --> 00:08:51.237 align:middle line:84%
back to that
commutation relation,

00:08:51.237 --> 00:08:53.320 align:middle line:84%
then you will get the
commutation relation with a.

00:08:53.320 --> 00:08:55.460 align:middle line:90%
So this is straightforward.

00:08:55.460 --> 00:08:58.540 align:middle line:84%
So if we call this
equation star--

00:08:58.540 --> 00:09:01.225 align:middle line:90%
star star, this equation star.

00:09:01.225 --> 00:09:03.880 align:middle line:90%


00:09:03.880 --> 00:09:20.180 align:middle line:84%
So plug star star into star,
and then we get the ak alpha ak

00:09:20.180 --> 00:09:32.870 align:middle line:84%
prime beta dagger should be
equal to beta alpha beta 2 pi

00:09:32.870 --> 00:09:40.710 align:middle line:90%
cubed delta -- prime OK.

00:09:40.710 --> 00:09:45.030 align:middle line:84%
And the the rest
commutators are all 0.

00:09:45.030 --> 00:09:53.500 align:middle line:90%


00:09:53.500 --> 00:09:56.005 align:middle line:84%
And then you can
define the vacuum.

00:09:56.005 --> 00:10:00.310 align:middle line:90%


00:10:00.310 --> 00:10:10.850 align:middle line:84%
Define a annihlated by all the
alphas for any alpha and k.

00:10:10.850 --> 00:10:15.300 align:middle line:90%


00:10:15.300 --> 00:10:20.580 align:middle line:84%
And I will introduce
the Hilbert space.

00:10:20.580 --> 00:10:25.245 align:middle line:90%
I call it H big to be the psi--

00:10:25.245 --> 00:10:28.740 align:middle line:90%


00:10:28.740 --> 00:10:42.930 align:middle line:84%
the collection of psi built by
acting ak alpha dagger on 0.

00:10:42.930 --> 00:10:45.630 align:middle line:90%
OK?

00:10:45.630 --> 00:10:50.370 align:middle line:84%
So you can just add arbitrary
number of them on 0,

00:10:50.370 --> 00:10:52.480 align:middle line:90%
then you get your Hilbert space.

00:10:52.480 --> 00:10:56.020 align:middle line:84%
So we call this Hilbert space
to be my big Hilbert space.

00:10:56.020 --> 00:11:00.960 align:middle line:84%
And you will see the
reason we do that.

00:11:00.960 --> 00:11:01.770 align:middle line:90%
OK?

00:11:01.770 --> 00:11:05.720 align:middle line:84%
So later, we will see
why we call this H big.

00:11:05.720 --> 00:11:09.670 align:middle line:90%
So this is seemingly all fine.

00:11:09.670 --> 00:11:12.090 align:middle line:84%
But of course,
there are problems.

00:11:12.090 --> 00:11:18.120 align:middle line:84%
This cannot be right, because
the Maxwell theory, we said,

00:11:18.120 --> 00:11:21.720 align:middle line:84%
only has two transverse
degrees of freedom.

00:11:21.720 --> 00:11:23.040 align:middle line:90%
But here we have four.

00:11:23.040 --> 00:11:25.140 align:middle line:84%
We have four massless
with degrees freedom.

00:11:25.140 --> 00:11:28.490 align:middle line:90%
We must have too many.

00:11:28.490 --> 00:11:34.280 align:middle line:84%
And indeed, you see
there, here, are problems.

00:11:34.280 --> 00:11:36.340 align:middle line:90%
So one problem is the following.

00:11:36.340 --> 00:11:40.210 align:middle line:90%


00:11:40.210 --> 00:11:44.218 align:middle line:90%
So one problem is the following.

00:11:44.218 --> 00:11:45.135 align:middle line:90%
So there are problems.

00:11:45.135 --> 00:11:48.670 align:middle line:90%


00:11:48.670 --> 00:11:50.070 align:middle line:90%
So one problem, yeah--

00:11:50.070 --> 00:11:52.740 align:middle line:84%
so the zeroth order
problem is that we

00:11:52.740 --> 00:12:02.940 align:middle line:84%
have four massless degrees
of freedom, two too many.

00:12:02.940 --> 00:12:03.440 align:middle line:90%
OK?

00:12:03.440 --> 00:12:07.590 align:middle line:90%


00:12:07.590 --> 00:12:12.270 align:middle line:84%
So we know that we only
should only have two.

00:12:12.270 --> 00:12:16.400 align:middle line:84%
And the second, you see
that this is problematic.

00:12:16.400 --> 00:12:20.640 align:middle line:90%


00:12:20.640 --> 00:12:22.140 align:middle line:90%
Is that, you notice--

00:12:22.140 --> 00:12:25.840 align:middle line:84%
so here, we have eta
alpha beta eta mu mu.

00:12:25.840 --> 00:12:30.270 align:middle line:84%
So this is all just from
Lorentz covariance, OK?

00:12:30.270 --> 00:12:34.720 align:middle line:84%
But this eta alpha
beta is problematic

00:12:34.720 --> 00:12:45.040 align:middle line:84%
because if you look at
the commutator for ak 0--

00:12:45.040 --> 00:12:46.090 align:middle line:90%
OK, so the zeros--

00:12:46.090 --> 00:12:50.410 align:middle line:90%


00:12:50.410 --> 00:13:01.450 align:middle line:84%
that polarization, then you
have ak 0 ak prime 0 dagger

00:13:01.450 --> 00:13:05.770 align:middle line:90%
equal to minus 2 pi cubed.

00:13:05.770 --> 00:13:07.345 align:middle line:90%
Say delta k minus k prime.

00:13:07.345 --> 00:13:09.910 align:middle line:90%


00:13:09.910 --> 00:13:11.110 align:middle line:90%
OK, you have a minus sign.

00:13:11.110 --> 00:13:15.290 align:middle line:90%


00:13:15.290 --> 00:13:21.670 align:middle line:84%
So this is problematic because
if we, say, create particles--

00:13:21.670 --> 00:13:37.850 align:middle line:84%
say if we create the particles
by acting ak alpha dagger

00:13:37.850 --> 00:13:46.450 align:middle line:84%
on the 0, and then you find,
because of this minus sign,

00:13:46.450 --> 00:14:04.980 align:middle line:84%
this create the particle with
polarization epsilon alpha mu.

00:14:04.980 --> 00:14:06.960 align:middle line:84%
So now, because of
this minus sign,

00:14:06.960 --> 00:14:13.140 align:middle line:84%
you see that if we look at the
overlap between the particle

00:14:13.140 --> 00:14:15.690 align:middle line:90%
with the 0 polarization--

00:14:15.690 --> 00:14:26.360 align:middle line:84%
so if we look at k 0
with some k prime 0--

00:14:26.360 --> 00:14:30.815 align:middle line:84%
and then because of this
minus sign, we have minus.

00:14:30.815 --> 00:14:33.680 align:middle line:90%


00:14:33.680 --> 00:14:40.940 align:middle line:84%
So this will be proportional
to minus 2 pi cube theta cube

00:14:40.940 --> 00:14:43.520 align:middle line:90%
k minus k.

00:14:43.520 --> 00:14:46.670 align:middle line:90%
So this is smaller than 0.

00:14:46.670 --> 00:14:49.835 align:middle line:84%
So you see, actually,
in the product--

00:14:49.835 --> 00:14:52.550 align:middle line:90%


00:14:52.550 --> 00:14:55.790 align:middle line:84%
so that means that this state
actually has negative norm.

00:14:55.790 --> 00:15:04.380 align:middle line:90%


00:15:04.380 --> 00:15:06.090 align:middle line:84%
That means this state
is negative norm.

00:15:06.090 --> 00:15:17.560 align:middle line:90%


00:15:17.560 --> 00:15:21.350 align:middle line:84%
But this is actually
a good sign.

00:15:21.350 --> 00:15:24.250 align:middle line:84%
So this is another way
to see that we have

00:15:24.250 --> 00:15:27.130 align:middle line:90%
too many degrees of freedom.

00:15:27.130 --> 00:15:30.850 align:middle line:84%
So that means not all degrees
of freedom here can be physical.

00:15:30.850 --> 00:15:34.390 align:middle line:84%
So here, it just tells you there
are some degree of freedom here

00:15:34.390 --> 00:15:38.370 align:middle line:84%
that must be unphysical because
they have negative norm.

00:15:38.370 --> 00:15:41.250 align:middle line:84%
The states they create
have negative norm.

00:15:41.250 --> 00:15:43.995 align:middle line:84%
So they cannot really correspond
to genuine physical states.

00:15:43.995 --> 00:15:50.100 align:middle line:90%


00:15:50.100 --> 00:15:54.090 align:middle line:84%
But those problems should
not worry us because, so far,

00:15:54.090 --> 00:15:57.720 align:middle line:84%
what we have done is to
quantize this theory.

00:15:57.720 --> 00:16:01.553 align:middle line:90%


00:16:01.553 --> 00:16:03.720 align:middle line:84%
So far what we have done
is to quantize this theory.

00:16:03.720 --> 00:16:06.780 align:middle line:84%
But this theory is not
the Maxwell theory.

00:16:06.780 --> 00:16:10.880 align:middle line:84%
To get the Maxwell theory,
we have to do two more steps.

00:16:10.880 --> 00:16:16.140 align:middle line:84%
One more step-- one step
is to impose conditions

00:16:16.140 --> 00:16:18.950 align:middle line:84%
so that makes sure this
partial mu a mu is equal to 0,

00:16:18.950 --> 00:16:21.860 align:middle line:84%
because we haven't
fixed the gauge.

00:16:21.860 --> 00:16:25.170 align:middle line:84%
The second condition,
we mentioned before.

00:16:25.170 --> 00:16:27.010 align:middle line:84%
So there are two more
things we need to.

00:16:27.010 --> 00:16:38.930 align:middle line:90%


00:16:38.930 --> 00:16:47.180 align:middle line:84%
So first is that we
need to ensure the gauge

00:16:47.180 --> 00:16:48.560 align:middle line:90%
partial mu A mu is equal to 0.

00:16:48.560 --> 00:16:52.340 align:middle line:90%


00:16:52.340 --> 00:16:55.680 align:middle line:84%
The second thing, as
we mentioned before,

00:16:55.680 --> 00:16:59.070 align:middle line:84%
is that after fixing
the Lorenz gauge,

00:16:59.070 --> 00:17:02.580 align:middle line:84%
they're still residual gauge
degrees of freedom left.

00:17:02.580 --> 00:17:09.000 align:middle line:84%
And we have to fix
the residual gauge

00:17:09.000 --> 00:17:10.500 align:middle line:90%
freedom in the Lorenz gauge.

00:17:10.500 --> 00:17:14.485 align:middle line:90%


00:17:14.485 --> 00:17:14.985 align:middle line:90%
OK?

00:17:14.985 --> 00:17:22.700 align:middle line:90%


00:17:22.700 --> 00:17:28.665 align:middle line:84%
So when you do this, then you
will get a physical Hilbert

00:17:28.665 --> 00:17:29.165 align:middle line:90%
space.

00:17:29.165 --> 00:17:31.753 align:middle line:90%


00:17:31.753 --> 00:17:33.420 align:middle line:84%
You will get the
physical Hilbert space.

00:17:33.420 --> 00:17:36.890 align:middle line:84%
And this physical Hilbert
space, we will see--

00:17:36.890 --> 00:17:40.490 align:middle line:84%
you will see-- will
only contain, indeed,

00:17:40.490 --> 00:17:43.700 align:middle line:84%
two transverse massless
degrees of freedom.

00:17:43.700 --> 00:17:49.340 align:middle line:84%
And the two degrees of freedom
