00:34:23.520 --> 00:34:24.690 align:middle line:90%
PROFESSOR: Yeah, exactly.

00:34:24.690 --> 00:34:29.048 align:middle line:84%
So the key is that the K
is actually not invertible.

00:34:29.048 --> 00:34:31.320 align:middle line:90%
Turns out K minus 1--

00:34:31.320 --> 00:34:38.639 align:middle line:84%
so K 0 actually
is not invertible.

00:34:38.639 --> 00:34:47.699 align:middle line:90%


00:34:47.699 --> 00:34:50.330 align:middle line:90%
So the reason is simple.

00:34:50.330 --> 00:34:52.550 align:middle line:84%
It's that because
the gauge freedom

00:34:52.550 --> 00:34:55.949 align:middle line:90%
in the original theory--

00:34:55.949 --> 00:34:58.950 align:middle line:84%
because the gauge freedom
in the original theory,

00:34:58.950 --> 00:35:03.360 align:middle line:84%
by gauge freedom, we mean that
when you make a transformation

00:35:03.360 --> 00:35:08.850 align:middle line:84%
by some arbitrary function,
your action does not change.

00:35:08.850 --> 00:35:13.440 align:middle line:84%
Then that means that this
kernel must be invariant

00:35:13.440 --> 00:35:17.070 align:middle line:90%
under some transformation.

00:35:17.070 --> 00:35:19.350 align:middle line:84%
It's invariant under
some transformation means

00:35:19.350 --> 00:35:22.170 align:middle line:84%
that this must have
zero eigenvector.

00:35:22.170 --> 00:35:25.290 align:middle line:84%
When it has zero
eigenvector, then they

00:35:25.290 --> 00:35:27.900 align:middle line:90%
must not be invertible.

00:35:27.900 --> 00:35:28.920 align:middle line:90%
OK?

00:35:28.920 --> 00:35:32.715 align:middle line:84%
So now let's just see it
explicitly.] To see it

00:35:32.715 --> 00:35:37.100 align:middle line:84%
explicitly, it's easier to
see this in momentum space.

00:35:37.100 --> 00:35:39.020 align:middle line:84%
So if we see this
in momentum space--

00:35:39.020 --> 00:35:48.052 align:middle line:90%


00:35:48.052 --> 00:35:50.260 align:middle line:84%
so in momentum space, we
can just directly write down

00:35:50.260 --> 00:35:53.470 align:middle line:90%
the K0 mu mu.

00:35:53.470 --> 00:35:59.220 align:middle line:84%
It's just equal to k
square, just k mu k

00:35:59.220 --> 00:36:04.240 align:middle line:90%
nu minus k square eta mu mu.

00:36:04.240 --> 00:36:10.310 align:middle line:90%


00:36:10.310 --> 00:36:14.180 align:middle line:84%
So now it's obvious this
has a zero eigenvector

00:36:14.180 --> 00:36:19.020 align:middle line:84%
because this is precisely
the minus k square,

00:36:19.020 --> 00:36:20.700 align:middle line:90%
the transverse projector.

00:36:20.700 --> 00:36:25.030 align:middle line:90%


00:36:25.030 --> 00:36:28.180 align:middle line:84%
So P mu nu T is the
projector into the direction

00:36:28.180 --> 00:36:30.820 align:middle line:90%
perpendicular to k mu.

00:36:30.820 --> 00:36:35.370 align:middle line:84%
So this satisfies the
property that pT mu

00:36:35.370 --> 00:36:44.490 align:middle line:84%
mu is equal to eta mu mu minus
k mu k mu divided by k square,

00:36:44.490 --> 00:36:50.905 align:middle line:84%
and satisfies the property p mu
mu T k nu is always equal to 0.

00:36:50.905 --> 00:36:51.405 align:middle line:90%
OK?

00:36:51.405 --> 00:36:56.770 align:middle line:90%


00:36:56.770 --> 00:36:58.480 align:middle line:84%
So you can easily see
it, because if you

00:36:58.480 --> 00:37:01.540 align:middle line:84%
contract with this k mu,
and k mu contract with here

00:37:01.540 --> 00:37:04.840 align:middle line:84%
and give you k square, and
cancel with k square here,

00:37:04.840 --> 00:37:07.940 align:middle line:84%
and you have k mu, and then
k mu contract with this one,

00:37:07.940 --> 00:37:08.710 align:middle line:90%
you just get k mu.

00:37:08.710 --> 00:37:11.110 align:middle line:90%
So they get canceled.

00:37:11.110 --> 00:37:13.450 align:middle line:84%
So this is the projector
to the transverse space.

00:37:13.450 --> 00:37:16.750 align:middle line:84%
Of course, it has
zero eigenvalue--

00:37:16.750 --> 00:37:18.020 align:middle line:90%
zero eigenvectors.

00:37:18.020 --> 00:37:21.490 align:middle line:90%


00:37:21.490 --> 00:37:25.000 align:middle line:84%
So then we see that this is not
invertible in momentum space,

00:37:25.000 --> 00:37:27.460 align:middle line:84%
and then it will not be
invertible in coordinate space.

00:37:27.460 --> 00:37:30.530 align:middle line:84%
It will not be invertible
in coordinate space.

00:37:30.530 --> 00:37:35.530 align:middle line:84%
And now, in coordinate
space, now we

00:37:35.530 --> 00:37:39.270 align:middle line:84%
can see with this
understanding, then

00:37:39.270 --> 00:37:42.740 align:middle line:84%
now we can immediately
see in coordinate space

00:37:42.740 --> 00:37:45.290 align:middle line:84%
the eigenvector
of zero eigenvalue

00:37:45.290 --> 00:37:48.240 align:middle line:84%
precisely corresponding
to a gauge transformation.

00:37:48.240 --> 00:37:56.950 align:middle line:90%


00:37:56.950 --> 00:38:04.990 align:middle line:84%
It's because in coordinate
space, k mu translate--

00:38:04.990 --> 00:38:09.930 align:middle line:84%
when you translate to coordinate
space, means partial mu.

00:38:09.930 --> 00:38:16.640 align:middle line:84%
So k mu to coordinate
space means partial mu.

00:38:16.640 --> 00:38:28.760 align:middle line:84%
So that means that for any
function, partial mu lambda--

00:38:28.760 --> 00:38:34.250 align:middle line:84%
this is K0 mu nu, partial
nu lambda must be 0.

00:38:34.250 --> 00:38:38.140 align:middle line:90%


00:38:38.140 --> 00:38:41.010 align:middle line:90%
And you can check explicitly.

00:38:41.010 --> 00:38:44.970 align:middle line:84%
So if you contract
with partial mu here,

00:38:44.970 --> 00:38:48.870 align:middle line:84%
and then you have a partial
square and you have partial mu,

00:38:48.870 --> 00:38:52.800 align:middle line:84%
and then eta mu mu will give you
partial mu, again, they cancel.

00:38:52.800 --> 00:38:54.900 align:middle line:84%
And of course, this is
just precisely the gauge

00:38:54.900 --> 00:38:57.000 align:middle line:90%
transformation.

00:38:57.000 --> 00:38:59.073 align:middle line:84%
This is precisely the
gauge transformation.

00:38:59.073 --> 00:39:03.150 align:middle line:90%


00:39:03.150 --> 00:39:05.230 align:middle line:84%
OK, so the gauge
transformation precisely

00:39:05.230 --> 00:39:09.330 align:middle line:84%
is the zero eigenvector
of this kernel.

00:39:09.330 --> 00:39:13.090 align:middle line:84%
It's the eigenvector of zero
eigenvalue of this kernel.

00:39:13.090 --> 00:39:15.090 align:middle line:84%
So that's why this
is not invertible.

00:39:15.090 --> 00:39:28.530 align:middle line:90%


00:39:28.530 --> 00:39:35.650 align:middle line:84%
So the way to fix is simple
because remember this picture.

00:39:35.650 --> 00:39:41.580 align:middle line:84%
So this is the space of the
full configurations of A mu.

00:39:41.580 --> 00:39:44.760 align:middle line:84%
And A mu along those
trajectories are equivalent.

00:39:44.760 --> 00:39:47.820 align:middle line:90%


00:39:47.820 --> 00:39:50.430 align:middle line:84%
To quantize it,
we need to just--

00:39:50.430 --> 00:39:52.470 align:middle line:84%
the physical configuration
corresponding

00:39:52.470 --> 00:39:54.940 align:middle line:90%
to a section of it.

00:39:54.940 --> 00:39:59.140 align:middle line:84%
So what this says
is that K0 is not

00:39:59.140 --> 00:40:02.440 align:middle line:84%
invertible in this full
space because you have

00:40:02.440 --> 00:40:05.253 align:middle line:84%
zero eigenvectors
along this direction,

00:40:05.253 --> 00:40:06.670 align:middle line:84%
OK, zero eigenvector
corresponding

00:40:06.670 --> 00:40:07.490 align:middle line:90%
to this direction.

00:40:07.490 --> 00:40:12.370 align:middle line:84%
But if we restrict to a
cross-section, and then

00:40:12.370 --> 00:40:15.220 align:middle line:84%
this zero eigenvector
no longer exists.

00:40:15.220 --> 00:40:17.350 align:middle line:90%
And then it will be invertible.

00:40:17.350 --> 00:40:21.370 align:middle line:84%
OK, so once we fix the
gauge, then we expect--

00:40:21.370 --> 00:40:24.760 align:middle line:84%
then the k mu after we fix the
gauge should be invertible.

00:40:24.760 --> 00:40:29.400 align:middle line:90%


00:40:29.400 --> 00:40:31.820 align:middle line:90%
Good?

00:40:31.820 --> 00:40:33.380 align:middle line:90%
So now let's fix the gauge.

00:40:33.380 --> 00:40:37.340 align:middle line:90%


00:40:37.340 --> 00:40:48.390 align:middle line:84%
So K0 mu nu restricted
to a section

00:40:48.390 --> 00:40:50.960 align:middle line:90%
should it be invertible.

00:40:50.960 --> 00:40:55.070 align:middle line:90%


00:40:55.070 --> 00:40:59.135 align:middle line:90%
OK, so we need to fix the gauge.

00:40:59.135 --> 00:41:06.700 align:middle line:90%


00:41:06.700 --> 00:41:09.660 align:middle line:84%
So we will do this
for the Lorenz gauge.

00:41:09.660 --> 00:41:13.830 align:middle line:84%
You can do similar things
for the Coulomb gauge.

00:41:13.830 --> 00:41:15.450 align:middle line:84%
The reason we do
the Lorenz gauge,

00:41:15.450 --> 00:41:20.650 align:middle line:84%
just the Lorenz gauge, later
when we introduce interactions,

00:41:20.650 --> 00:41:23.040 align:middle line:84%
we will always work
with the Lorenz gauge.

00:41:23.040 --> 00:41:24.855 align:middle line:84%
And when we discuss
QED, we will always

00:41:24.855 --> 00:41:25.980 align:middle line:90%
work with the Lorenz gauge.

00:41:25.980 --> 00:41:28.860 align:middle line:84%
So here I will elaborate
in the Lorenz gauge.

00:41:28.860 --> 00:41:29.730 align:middle line:90%
Yes?

00:41:29.730 --> 00:41:31.180 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: Can you
