00:42:41.000 --> 00:42:42.110 align:middle line:90%
PROFESSOR: Yeah.

00:42:42.110 --> 00:42:48.580 align:middle line:84%
Because other symmetries--
you have local symmetries.

00:42:48.580 --> 00:42:50.460 align:middle line:84%
So the local symmetry
tells you there's

00:42:50.460 --> 00:42:52.980 align:middle line:84%
really some degree
of freedom redundant.

00:42:52.980 --> 00:42:55.530 align:middle line:84%
So this is really
corresponding to--

00:42:55.530 --> 00:43:00.240 align:middle line:84%
so this lambda x, so all
possible choice of lambda,

00:43:00.240 --> 00:43:04.290 align:middle line:84%
is really corresponding
to some finite trajectory

00:43:04.290 --> 00:43:06.370 align:middle line:90%
in your configuration space.

00:43:06.370 --> 00:43:07.890 align:middle line:84%
So if you have a
global symmetry,

00:43:07.890 --> 00:43:10.870 align:middle line:84%
global symmetry is
independent of coordinates.

00:43:10.870 --> 00:43:13.470 align:middle line:84%
So from this point of
view, a global symmetry

00:43:13.470 --> 00:43:16.050 align:middle line:84%
just relates to the
configuration at this point

00:43:16.050 --> 00:43:20.400 align:middle line:84%
to the configuration at that
point and at that point.

00:43:20.400 --> 00:43:23.820 align:middle line:84%
A global symmetry, because
it's independent of spacetime,

00:43:23.820 --> 00:43:28.040 align:middle line:84%
that transformation
doesn't change your number

00:43:28.040 --> 00:43:29.590 align:middle line:90%
of degrees of freedom.

00:43:29.590 --> 00:43:31.930 align:middle line:84%
They don't correspond
to actually a trajectory

00:43:31.930 --> 00:43:33.700 align:middle line:90%
in your configuration space.

00:43:33.700 --> 00:43:37.540 align:middle line:90%


00:43:37.540 --> 00:43:38.260 align:middle line:90%
Good.

