00:58:17.800 --> 00:58:23.178 align:middle line:84%
And now we can straightforwardly
calculate-- now we

00:58:23.178 --> 00:58:25.470 align:middle line:84%
can straightforwardly calculate
this Gaussian integral.

00:58:25.470 --> 00:58:32.740 align:middle line:90%


00:58:32.740 --> 00:58:33.250 align:middle line:90%
One second.

00:58:33.250 --> 00:58:37.008 align:middle line:90%


00:58:37.008 --> 00:58:39.050 align:middle line:84%
Yeah, now we can just
straightforwardly calculate

00:58:39.050 --> 00:58:39.633 align:middle line:90%
this integral.

00:58:39.633 --> 00:59:05.260 align:middle line:90%


00:59:05.260 --> 00:59:14.490 align:middle line:84%
By the way, the reason I say
the story here is trivial,

00:59:14.490 --> 00:59:17.060 align:middle line:84%
it's a little bit of
killing a bird with--

00:59:17.060 --> 00:59:19.580 align:middle line:84%
it's because for
the Maxwell case,

00:59:19.580 --> 00:59:22.010 align:middle line:84%
this Jacobian is
actually trivial.

00:59:22.010 --> 00:59:23.100 align:middle line:90%
It's a constant.

00:59:23.100 --> 00:59:25.340 align:middle line:84%
But if you do it for a
non-Abelian gauge theory,

00:59:25.340 --> 00:59:28.430 align:middle line:84%
say, for the electroweak
theory or for QCD,

00:59:28.430 --> 00:59:30.980 align:middle line:84%
this Jacobian is
highly non-trivial.

00:59:30.980 --> 00:59:34.070 align:middle line:84%
And part of this
trick is also how

00:59:34.070 --> 00:59:37.520 align:middle line:84%
to treat this Jacobian, which
we don't have to do here.

00:59:37.520 --> 00:59:40.550 align:middle line:84%
So here we have a
much simpler story.

00:59:40.550 --> 00:59:44.000 align:middle line:84%
So now we can just look at
this path integral, which

00:59:44.000 --> 00:59:47.300 align:middle line:84%
now S xi become invertible,
because we already know

00:59:47.300 --> 00:59:49.730 align:middle line:90%
from here this is invertible.

00:59:49.730 --> 00:59:52.010 align:middle line:84%
At least for xi equal
to 1, given by this,

00:59:52.010 --> 00:59:54.080 align:middle line:90%
this is invertible.

00:59:54.080 --> 00:59:58.290 align:middle line:90%
So you can actually now invert.

00:59:58.290 --> 01:00:12.220 align:middle line:84%
So now we can write this S xi is
equal to 1/2 d4x A mu x K mu --

01:00:12.220 --> 01:00:16.870 align:middle line:90%
K mu nu xi x minus y A nu y.

01:00:16.870 --> 01:00:19.920 align:middle line:90%


01:00:19.920 --> 01:00:21.220 align:middle line:90%
And this K mu nu--

01:00:21.220 --> 01:00:25.680 align:middle line:90%


01:00:25.680 --> 01:00:30.630 align:middle line:84%
yeah, K mu nu just whatever
you get from that thing,

01:00:30.630 --> 01:00:32.370 align:middle line:84%
just whatever you
get from that thing.

01:00:32.370 --> 01:00:37.800 align:middle line:84%
And then the K mu mu
now is invertible.

01:00:37.800 --> 01:00:44.690 align:middle line:84%
And then you find this thing
just becomes some constant,

01:00:44.690 --> 01:00:58.060 align:middle line:84%
then exponential i d4x
d4y J mu x, then K xi

01:00:58.060 --> 01:01:05.780 align:middle line:90%
minus 1 mu nu x minus 1 J nu y.

01:01:05.780 --> 01:01:07.550 align:middle line:90%
OK?

01:01:07.550 --> 01:01:11.420 align:middle line:84%
And again, this inverse gives
you the Feynman function.

01:01:11.420 --> 01:01:14.230 align:middle line:90%


01:01:14.230 --> 01:01:18.070 align:middle line:84%
Again, this gives you
the Feynman function.

01:01:18.070 --> 01:01:21.730 align:middle line:90%
So the K xi minus 1 mu mu--

01:01:21.730 --> 01:01:24.500 align:middle line:90%


01:01:24.500 --> 01:01:25.280 align:middle line:90%
or mu nu.

01:01:25.280 --> 01:01:30.770 align:middle line:90%


01:01:30.770 --> 01:01:32.630 align:middle line:84%
Yeah, so we're not
going into detail here.

01:01:32.630 --> 01:01:34.380 align:middle line:90%
The story is straightforward.

01:01:34.380 --> 01:01:45.350 align:middle line:84%
So this should correspond
to the Feynman function

01:01:45.350 --> 01:01:48.290 align:middle line:90%
for the two gauge fields.

01:01:48.290 --> 01:01:56.977 align:middle line:90%


01:01:56.977 --> 01:01:59.060 align:middle line:84%
OK, this should correspond
to the Feynman function

01:01:59.060 --> 01:02:02.250 align:middle line:90%
of these two gauge fields.

01:02:02.250 --> 01:02:05.410 align:middle line:84%
So now let me just
write down the answer.

01:02:05.410 --> 01:02:09.910 align:middle line:84%
So I urge you to check
it yourself explicitly.

01:02:09.910 --> 01:02:13.900 align:middle line:84%
So you can easily write
down what is K mu nu here.

01:02:13.900 --> 01:02:20.050 align:middle line:84%
And then you need to write
down what is K mu nu here,

01:02:20.050 --> 01:02:26.920 align:middle line:84%
and then you can write
down what is the K minus 1.

01:02:26.920 --> 01:02:30.280 align:middle line:84%
So let me just write down
the answer, which we actually

01:02:30.280 --> 01:02:34.780 align:middle line:84%
will use later for the
Feynman diagram calculation.

01:02:34.780 --> 01:02:43.050 align:middle line:84%
OK, so you can show this given
by a momentum space minus i k

01:02:43.050 --> 01:02:45.090 align:middle line:90%
squared minus i epsilon.

01:02:45.090 --> 01:02:47.460 align:middle line:84%
Remember, now,
here it's massless.

01:02:47.460 --> 01:02:51.070 align:middle line:90%
And you have eta mu nu minus--

01:02:51.070 --> 01:03:00.840 align:middle line:84%
plus xi minus 1 k mu k
nu divided by k squared.

01:03:00.840 --> 01:03:04.550 align:middle line:90%


01:03:04.550 --> 01:03:08.620 align:middle line:84%
So you can work out the
inverse given by this.

01:03:08.620 --> 01:03:16.250 align:middle line:84%
And so this can also be written
in terms to the minus i k

01:03:16.250 --> 01:03:17.945 align:middle line:90%
squared plus i epsilon.

01:03:17.945 --> 01:03:23.160 align:middle line:90%


01:03:23.160 --> 01:03:25.770 align:middle line:84%
You can write it in terms of
this transverse projector,

01:03:25.770 --> 01:03:37.760 align:middle line:84%
k mu mu t, then
plus xi P mu nu L.

01:03:37.760 --> 01:03:45.120 align:middle line:84%
So P mu nu L is the
longitudinal projector.

01:03:45.120 --> 01:03:51.900 align:middle line:84%
You just define it by k mu
k nu divided by k squared.

01:03:51.900 --> 01:03:53.520 align:middle line:90%
That's divided by k squared.

01:03:53.520 --> 01:03:56.740 align:middle line:90%


01:03:56.740 --> 01:03:58.715 align:middle line:84%
So this is an
answer very simple.

01:03:58.715 --> 01:04:01.310 align:middle line:90%


01:04:01.310 --> 01:04:04.860 align:middle line:90%
So now the interesting thing--

01:04:04.860 --> 01:04:06.750 align:middle line:84%
the two interesting
things here--

01:04:06.750 --> 01:04:11.985 align:middle line:90%


01:04:11.985 --> 01:04:13.360 align:middle line:84%
so let me just
make some remarks.

01:04:13.360 --> 01:04:20.580 align:middle line:90%


01:04:20.580 --> 01:04:31.900 align:middle line:84%
So first, if you look
at xi equal to 1,

01:04:31.900 --> 01:04:35.530 align:middle line:84%
then this term
vanishes, and then

01:04:35.530 --> 01:04:40.210 align:middle line:84%
you just have eta mu divided
by k squared minus i epsilon.

01:04:40.210 --> 01:04:44.240 align:middle line:84%
So that's exactly what
we expect from here.

01:04:44.240 --> 01:04:51.050 align:middle line:84%
So here, you just essentially
have the massless 1 over k

01:04:51.050 --> 01:04:55.480 align:middle line:84%
square propagator for
the massless particle.

01:04:55.480 --> 01:05:02.410 align:middle line:84%
And then you have eta mu mu
from the Lorenz signature.

01:05:02.410 --> 01:05:05.605 align:middle line:84%
So for eta equal to 1-- xi equal
to 1, indeed we covered that.

01:05:05.605 --> 01:05:08.570 align:middle line:90%


01:05:08.570 --> 01:05:10.855 align:middle line:84%
So comment is that
when xi is equal to 0.

01:05:10.855 --> 01:05:14.740 align:middle line:90%


01:05:14.740 --> 01:05:17.530 align:middle line:84%
so this is just proportional
to the transverse projector.

01:05:17.530 --> 01:05:21.240 align:middle line:90%


01:05:21.240 --> 01:05:22.510 align:middle line:90%
To the transverse projector.

01:05:22.510 --> 01:05:28.410 align:middle line:84%
But remember, the
original Maxwell action,

01:05:28.410 --> 01:05:29.820 align:middle line:90%
we used xi equal to 0.

01:05:29.820 --> 01:05:31.290 align:middle line:90%
Actually, that's not invertible.

01:05:31.290 --> 01:05:34.110 align:middle line:90%


01:05:34.110 --> 01:05:36.890 align:middle line:84%
So here, we're actually
doing a different order.

01:05:36.890 --> 01:05:39.180 align:middle line:90%
We first take a nonzero xi.

01:05:39.180 --> 01:05:40.680 align:middle line:90%
We invert it.

01:05:40.680 --> 01:05:43.350 align:middle line:84%
And then you can set
actually xi equal to 0.

01:05:43.350 --> 01:05:44.920 align:middle line:90%
OK, that's still works.

01:05:44.920 --> 01:05:48.720 align:middle line:84%
And then xi equal to 0 still
works, because we already

01:05:48.720 --> 01:05:50.010 align:middle line:90%
fixed the gauge.

01:05:50.010 --> 01:05:53.232 align:middle line:90%
We already fixed the gauge.

01:05:53.232 --> 01:05:54.440 align:middle line:90%
So this is the second remark.

01:05:54.440 --> 01:05:59.500 align:middle line:90%


01:05:59.500 --> 01:06:07.480 align:middle line:84%
And then the Wick's
theorem for A mu

01:06:07.480 --> 01:06:10.540 align:middle line:84%
just immediately
follows from here.

01:06:10.540 --> 01:06:18.391 align:middle line:84%
Just as in the case for the
scalars and the fermions,

01:06:18.391 --> 01:06:19.750 align:middle line:90%
it immediately follows.

01:06:19.750 --> 01:06:28.240 align:middle line:90%


01:06:28.240 --> 01:06:29.090 align:middle line:90%
You just contract.

01:06:29.090 --> 01:06:33.020 align:middle line:84%
We all get these Feynman
functions between them.

01:06:33.020 --> 01:06:33.652 align:middle line:90%
Yes?

01:06:33.652 --> 01:06:35.110 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: How
difficult would it be

01:06:35.110 --> 01:06:37.840 align:middle line:84%
